Yandex.Afisha Optimize Marketing Expenses Project¶

Author: Alexander Feldman v.1.3

Project description¶

Customer - Analytical department at Yandex.Afisha.
The goal of project is to help optimize marketing expenses.

Sources:¶

  • Server logs with data on Yandex.Afisha visits from June 2017 through May 2018
  • Dump file with all orders for the period
  • Marketing expenses statistics #### Issues to study:
  • How people use the product
  • When they start to buy
  • How much money each customer brings
  • When they pay off

Table of Contents¶

  1. Opening the data and preprocessing.
  2. Exploratory data analysis (EDA).
    2.1 Product.
    2.2 Sales.
    2.3 Marketing.
  3. Conclusion and recommendations.

# rename some label of columns and convert ones to lowercase
visits.columns = visits.columns.str.lower()
visits = visits.rename(columns={'end ts':'end_ts', 'source id':'source_id', 'start ts':'start_ts'})
orders.columns = orders.columns.str.lower()
orders = orders.rename(columns={'buy ts':'buy_date'})
orders.loc[50414, 'buy_date'] = '2018-05-31' #change mistaked value  '2018-06-01' to close right 
orders['buy_date'] = orders['buy_date'].astype('datetime64[D]')
costs = costs.rename(columns={'dt':'date_costs'})

The datasets are ready for analysis.

  • How many people use it every day, week, and month?
  • How many sessions are there per day? (One user might have more than one session.)
  • What is the length of each session?

In [34]:
# Found out the retantion rate
visits['visits_date'] = pd.to_datetime(visits['visits_date'])
visits['visits_month'] = pd.to_datetime(visits['visits_month'])
first_visits_month = visits.groupby('uid')['visits_date'].min()
first_visits_month.name = 'first_visits_month'
first_visits_month = first_visits_month.astype('datetime64[M]')
visits = visits.join(first_visits_month, on='uid')
In [35]:
visits['cohort_lifetime'] = visits['visits_month'] - visits['first_visits_month']
visits['cohort_lifetime'] = visits['cohort_lifetime'] / np.timedelta64(1,'M')
visits['cohort_lifetime'] = visits['cohort_lifetime'].astype(int)
cohorts = visits.groupby(['first_visits_month','cohort_lifetime']).agg({'uid':'nunique'}).reset_index()
initial_users_count = cohorts[cohorts['cohort_lifetime'] == 0][['first_visits_month','uid']]
initial_users_count = initial_users_count.rename(columns={'uid':'cohort_users'})
cohorts = cohorts.merge(initial_users_count,on='first_visits_month')
cohorts['retention'] = cohorts['uid']/cohorts['cohort_users']
retention_pivot = cohorts.pivot_table(index='first_visits_month',columns='cohort_lifetime',
                                      values='retention',aggfunc='sum').reset_index()
retention_pivot['first_visits_month']= retention_pivot['first_visits_month'].dt.strftime('%Y-%m')
retention_pivot = retention_pivot.set_index('first_visits_month')
In [36]:
retention_pivot = retention_pivot.drop([0], axis=1)

plt.title('Cohorts: User Retention')

# Found out the Churn rate
cohorts['churn_rate'] = cohorts.groupby(['first_visits_month'])['uid'].pct_change()
churn_pivot = cohorts.pivot_table(index='first_visits_month',
                                  columns='cohort_lifetime',values='churn_rate',aggfunc='sum').reset_index()
churn_pivot['first_visits_month']= churn_pivot['first_visits_month'].dt.strftime('%Y-%m')
churn_pivot = churn_pivot.set_index('first_visits_month')
plt.figure(figsize=(13, 11))
sns.heatmap(churn_pivot, annot=True, fmt='.1%', linewidths=1, linecolor='gray', cmap='Pastel2_r')
plt.title('The user churn rate by cohorts by time', fontdict={'size':15})
plt.ylabel('Cohorts')
plt.xlabel('Cohorts life time')
plt.show()

  1. Use of the service.

  • Every day the service use from 1 to 3319 people. The average daily activity users are 908 people per day.
  • Every week the service use from 2364 to 10586 unique users. The average weekly activity users are 5825 people per week.
  • Every month the service use from 11631 to 32797 unique users. The average monthly activity users are 23228 people per month.
    </ul>
  1. The number of sessions.
  • Every day the service has from 1 to 4042 sessions. The average value is 987 sessions per day.
  • In average user has 1.58 sessions per day. From 1 to 893 ones.
    </ul>
  1. The length of sessions.
  • The average session length is: 10 minutes 43 sec.
    </ul>
  1. How often do users come back?
  • Weekly sticky factor is 18.07%. Monthly sticky factor is 4.41%. I think this factor is more suitable for measuring the loyalty of the audience of games than information resources and online stores. Users do not constantly sit in Yandex.afisha, but make visits when they want to go to the theater or to a concert. In this case, the Lifetime indicator will tell us more about loyalty.
  • Total conversion rating is: 16.01%.
  • Retation rate decreases to an average of 6.06% after the first month and then to an average of 4.82% in subsequent months.
  • Churn rate decreases to an average of -93.94% after the first month and then changes in both directions depending on the seasonю. The average value is -18.43%. </ul>

Sales ¶

  • When do people start buying? (In KPI analysis, we're usually interested in knowing the time that elapses between registration and conversion — when the user becomes a customer. For example, if registration and the first purchase occur on the same day, the user might fall into category Conversion 0d. If the first purchase happens the next day, it will be Conversion 1d. You can use any approach that lets you compare the conversions of different cohorts, so that you can determine which cohort, or marketing channel, is most effective.)
  • How many orders do they make during a given period of time?
  • What is the average purchase size?
  • How much money do they bring? (LTV).

# Study time of conversion by source
users_per_source = visits.groupby('uid')['source_id'].mean().astype('int')

time_conv_sources = orders.groupby('source_id')['conv_time'].mean().reset_index()
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
rect=ax.bar(time_conv_sources['source_id'], time_conv_sources['conv_time'], color='brown')
ax.set_ylabel('Conversion time, days')
ax.set_xlabel('Sources')
ax.set_title('The average conversion time by sources', fontdict={'size':15})
for row in time_conv_sources.itertuples():
    ax.text(row.source_id, row.conv_time-2, s=str(int(row.conv_time))+' d',
            fontdict={'horizontalalignment': 'center','size':11, 'color':'white'})
plt.show()

How we can see the smallest conversion time has 10th source (5 days) and the largest conversion time belong of the 8th (free) (45 days) and 9th sources (31 days).

print("LTV for period 12 months (in fact it's ARPU) is {:.2f} usd".format(pivot_cohort['LTV'].mean()))

LTV for period 12 months (in fact it's ARPU) is 7.28 usd

Due to the fact that the lifetime of the cohorts exceeds the studied period (12 months), we cannot accurately determine the life time of cohorts and therefore we cannot determine LTV.

Looking at the graph, we can say that after a zero month of explosive sales over the next months, approximately 10-15% of the cohort users continue to buy on the service (By the way, here we can see the true loyalty of the audience. The previously calculated sticky factor showed a lower result). Fluctuations in these sales are more seasonal than cohort life time. It can be assumed that the further life cycle of cohorts will depend on the life cycle of the service. Until the service itself becomes morally obsolete or a more successful competitor appears that will entice the audience to itself, the cohorts will live on.

Thus, we cannot determine the lifetime and LTV, but we can calculate how many lifetimes and LTV is required in order for the investment to pay off and the investors to make a profit. I can do it after calculating CAC.

    for rect in rects:

        ax.annotate('{:.2f}'.format(height),
                    xy=(rect.get_x() + rect.get_width() / 2, height),
                    xytext=(0, 3),  # 3 points vertical offset
                    textcoords="offset points",

In [86]:
romi_cohort_months['cac'] = romi_cohort_months['costs'] / romi_cohort_months['n_cohrt_custmrs']
romi_cohort_months['romi'] = romi_cohort_months['arpu'] / romi_cohort_months['cac']
romi_cohort_months['cum_arpu'] = romi_cohort_months['arpu']
for i in range(1, len(romi_cohort_months)): # Need to repeat because com_arpu.shift() doesn't work without it
    romi_cohort_months['cum_arpu'] = np.where(romi_cohort_months['cac']>0,
                                              romi_cohort_months['arpu'],                        
                                              romi_cohort_months['arpu'] + romi_cohort_months['cum_arpu'].shift())
romi_cohort_months['fix_cac'] = romi_cohort_months['cac']
for i in range(1, len(romi_cohort_months)):
    romi_cohort_months['fix_cac'] = np.where(romi_cohort_months['cac']>0,
                                      romi_cohort_months['cac'],
                                      romi_cohort_months['fix_cac'].shift())
romi_cohort_months['cum_romi'] = romi_cohort_months['cum_arpu'] / romi_cohort_months['fix_cac']

3. Conclusion and recommendations ¶

  • We see that after 12 months the project has a negative financial result and a large accumulated loss. It should be borne in mind that the project was in the stage of rapid growth and required high costs to attract an audience. The loss shown is of a planned nature.
  • Cohort analysis showed us that out of 12 cohorts during the year, only 2 cohorts justified the costs: the very first (June) with the longest life time, as well as the September one, which for some reason showed an explosive sales result in December. However, the analysis of the average monthly revenue per user in the coming months is very encouraging. It looks like the cohorts will not expire for natural reasons. Fluctuations in monthly revenue are seasonal. Most likely, the life cycle of cohorts will coincide with the life cycle of the service as a whole, until users find an alternative. To prevent this from happening, marketing should be very careful to monitor competitors, since the loss of customers will be irreparable.
  • Analysis of the life cycle of the cohorts showed us that while maintaining the existing state of the service, the payback time for the remaining cohorts varies from 5 to 30 months, the average value is 9.5 months. In order to speed up these processes, marketing should work on increasing ARPU for the longest cohorts (especially January and February).
  • It is worthwhile to study the case of the September cohort in more detail and find out what exactly is the reason for such a success in December. If possible, it is worth repeating this trick next year.
  • Causes the madness of losses that are brought by source 3, which is the leader in terms of costs. On the one hand, the source has the largest number of attracted clients, on the other hand, these clients spend significantly less than clients from other sources. As a result, customers bring in less revenue than the cost of acquiring them. The negative profitability of the 3rd source is the main reason for the negative result of the project. The marketing department needs to plan marketing activities and develop a model to increase the following parameters: average purchase size, average number of orders per customer. At the time of implementation of the model, it is necessary to reduce costs in source 3 several times and redistribute these investments to sources 1 and 2, which have high profitability rates.
  • Is it worth studying in more detail why smartphone users (with touch device) use the service noticeably less? Perhaps there are some problems or inconveniences with the mobile version of the site or app.
